      <article class="post-content">

        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p>A <strong>shadowban</strong> is when a social media platform quietly suppresses your content's visibility without sending any notification. Your posts stop appearing in hashtag pages, the Explore feed, and search results — but you can still post normally and have no indication anything has changed. Creators report sudden <strong>80-90% drops</strong> in organic reach that resolve mysteriously after 1-3 weeks.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Reach drop</div>
            <div class="tms-value">80-90% typical</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Social Media</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Recovery time</div>
            <div class="tms-value">1-3 weeks</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Beginner</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">The most damaging aspect of a shadowban isn't the reach drop — it's the silence. Without notification, creators blame content quality and change strategies unnecessarily. Recognising a shadowban early stops wasted effort and speeds recovery.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is a shadowban?</h2>
        <p>A shadowban is a form of content suppression where a platform's algorithm reduces the distribution of an account's posts without informing the account holder. The term originated from online forums where moderators silently blocked users without their knowledge.</p>
        <p>On social platforms, a shadowban means:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Posts no longer appear in <strong>hashtag pages</strong> for non-followers</li>
          <li>Content is hidden from <strong>Explore / Discover / For You</strong> feeds</li>
          <li>Posts don't appear in <strong>search results</strong> for non-followers</li>
          <li>The account can still post, comment, and like normally</li>
          <li>The account holder receives <strong>no notification</strong> from the platform</li>
        </ul>
        <p>Most platforms (Instagram, TikTok) officially deny that shadowbanning exists. Despite this, the experience of sudden, unexplained reach suppression is widely documented across creator communities, with consistent patterns of triggers and recovery behaviour.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Platform stances on shadowbanning</div>
          <p>Instagram and TikTok officially deny the existence of shadowbanning. Twitter/X has acknowledged forms of "visibility filtering" in its content policies. Meta's transparency reports acknowledge content that "reduces distribution" without removal. The practice exists under different names across platforms — what matters is knowing how to detect and resolve it.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why shadowbans matter for content creators and brands</h2>
        <p>A shadowban creates four compounding problems:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Revenue loss.</strong> Creators earning from brand partnerships rely on reach metrics. A 90% reach drop eliminates the numbers brands pay for, freezing new deals and potentially voiding existing ones with performance clauses.</li>
          <li><strong>Wasted content investment.</strong> Hours spent creating videos, carousels, and copy reaches almost no one. Every post during a shadowban is near-zero-ROI effort.</li>
          <li><strong>Misdiagnosis.</strong> Without knowing about the shadowban, creators change their content strategy, posting frequency, and creative format — solving the wrong problem while the real issue persists.</li>
          <li><strong>Compounding algorithm signal.</strong> Low engagement from suppressed posts signals to the algorithm that content is poor quality, potentially extending the suppression beyond the initial trigger period.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How shadowbans work — triggers and mechanics</h2>
        <p>Platforms use automated systems to detect and suppress content that violates guidelines or exhibits spam-like patterns. The suppression is graduated — not an outright ban — which is why reach drops dramatically rather than going to zero.</p>

        <h3>Common shadowban triggers</h3>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Banned hashtags</strong> — using hashtags flagged by the platform for spam or inappropriate content</li>
          <li><strong>Excessive posting frequency</strong> — posting more than 5-6 times per day triggers spam detection</li>
          <li><strong>Third-party automation tools</strong> — bots for following, liking, or scheduling via unofficial APIs</li>
          <li><strong>Content report spikes</strong> — multiple users reporting a post in a short window</li>
          <li><strong>Borderline community guideline violations</strong> — content AI systems flag as potentially violating, even without human review</li>
          <li><strong>Sudden account activity bursts</strong> — batch-uploading many posts in a single session, mimicking bot behaviour</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="types">Types of content suppression — shadowban vs other restrictions</h2>

        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Type</th><th>Notification</th><th>Can post?</th><th>Reach impact</th><th>Duration</th></tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr class="row-highlight">
                <td><strong>Shadowban</strong></td>
                <td class="cell-no">None</td>
                <td class="cell-yes">Yes</td>
