              <tr><td><strong>Account suspension</strong></td><td class="cell-yes">Yes</td><td class="cell-no">No</td><td class="cell-no">Total</td><td>Days to permanent</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Reduced distribution</strong></td><td class="cell-no">None</td><td class="cell-yes">Yes</td><td class="cell-meh">20-50% drop</td><td>Ongoing</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <h2 id="examples">Real shadowban examples</h2>

        <h3>Example 1: Fitness creator on Instagram</h3>
        <p>A fitness creator's Reel reach dropped from 15,000 average to 400 views overnight — a 97% drop. She checked her hashtags using a secondary account and discovered she'd used a recently restricted hashtag (#fitnessmotivation had been flagged). After removing the hashtag from future posts and taking a 48-hour break, reach recovered within a week.</p>

        <h3>Example 2: Small business TikTok account</h3>
        <p>A bakery tried batch-uploading 8 videos in one day after spending a weekend filming. TikTok's algorithm detected the burst activity as spam-like behaviour and suppressed the account. Reach dropped to near-zero for 5 days before recovering. The correct approach: schedule posts 2-3 hours apart across multiple days using TikTok's native scheduler, not third-party tools.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Shadowban vs algorithm suppression — what's the difference?</h2>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Shadowban</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Sudden onset — drops 80-90% overnight</li>
              <li>Triggered by a specific action or content</li>
              <li>Temporary — typically resolves in 1-3 weeks</li>
              <li>Affects reach to non-followers primarily</li>
              <li>Recovery: remove triggers, posting break</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Algorithmic reach decline</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Gradual — drops over weeks or months</li>
              <li>Caused by declining content engagement</li>
              <li>Permanent without content quality improvement</li>
              <li>Affects all distribution channels</li>
              <li>Recovery: higher-quality, engaging content</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="how-to-detect">How to detect a shadowban</h2>
        <p>The most reliable detection method is a secondary account check:</p>
        <ol>
          <li>Post content with a specific hashtag</li>
          <li>Log out and check that hashtag page from a different account (one that doesn't follow you)</li>
          <li>If your post doesn't appear in the hashtag feed within 30 minutes, you are likely shadowbanned</li>
          <li>Confirm by checking analytics: a 70%+ sudden drop in reach or impressions with no change in posting behaviour indicates shadowban</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="best-practices">6 best practices to avoid shadowbans</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Research hashtags before using them.</strong> Search each hashtag on the platform. If the most recent posts are days old, the hashtag may be restricted or flagged.</li>
          <li><strong>Limit posting frequency.</strong> On Instagram and TikTok, 3-4 posts per day is the safe upper limit. Batch creation is fine — batch posting is not.</li>
          <li><strong>Use only native platform tools.</strong> Avoid third-party automation — scheduling tools that use official APIs (Meta Business Suite, TikTok's native scheduler) are safe. Tools that simulate human interaction via browser automation are not.</li>
          <li><strong>Review content for borderline guideline violations.</strong> AI moderation is aggressive. Health, political, and sexual content categories are highest risk. Err on the side of caution with anything ambiguous.</li>
          <li><strong>Engage genuinely before and after posting.</strong> Spending 10-15 minutes engaging with related content before posting signals authentic platform behaviour to detection algorithms.</li>
          <li><strong>Monitor reach analytics weekly.</strong> Catch suppression early by tracking week-over-week reach. A 50%+ single-week drop with no content change is the early warning signal.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — continuing to post during a shadowban</div>
          <p>Many creators try to "post through" a shadowban by uploading more content. This is counterproductive. Every new post during suppression shows near-zero engagement, sending negative signals to the algorithm and potentially extending the suppression. Take a 24-48 hour break, remove known triggers, then resume with your best content.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common shadowban mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Using the same hashtag set on every post</strong> — platforms interpret repetitive patterns as automation</li>
          <li><strong>Posting more than 30 hashtags per post on Instagram</strong> — Instagram specifically flags heavy hashtag use as spam-like</li>
          <li><strong>Using third-party tools that access the API unofficially</strong> — almost guaranteed to trigger detection</li>
          <li><strong>Deleting and reposting flagged content</strong> — the content signature is flagged, not just the post ID</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring the detection test</strong> — never knowing you're shadowbanned means weeks of wasted effort</li>
        </ul>

